name: North Central DPH
tweet: Still holding on to those #Thanksgiving leftovers? Know when to toss: you can’t tell by looking or smelling whether harmful bacteria have started growing in your leftovers or refrigerated foods.  https://t.co/oskfxZiIHU

name: North Central DPH

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Thank you for following us through #TheStoryOfYourDinner this #Thanksgiving! Food safety is important on the holidays and every day of the year. Take these tips and keep your family safe from foodborne illness! Happy Thanksgiving!  https://t.co/15FGE4MyLl

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Refrigerate or freeze perishables, prepared foods and leftovers within two hours of purchase or use. If the temperature is 90˚F or above, cut this time down to one hour. Separate large amounts of leftovers into shallow containers for quicker cooling. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/qAT9m5KbH4

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Food is cooked safely when it reaches a high enough internal temperature to kill the harmful bacteria that cause illness. Use a food thermometer to measure the internal temperature of cooked foods. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/sz9BRgsFkU

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Always follow the cooking instructions when preparing packaged foods. Instructions include information like cook temperature and cook time to ensure that the food reaches the proper internal temperature. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/8kr0T82fQ1

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Use one cutting board for fresh produce and a separate one for raw meat, poultry and seafood. Never place cooked food back on a plate that previously held raw meat, poultry, seafood or eggs. Wash plates with hot water and soap before using with other foods. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/fM9J9SPkju

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Rinse fresh fruits and veggies under running water just before eating, even if you plan to cut or peel them, because bacteria can spread from the outside to the inside during cutting or peeling. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/LusOCvUw7N

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Don't rinse meat or poultry in the sink. Doing so can lead to contamination of surfaces, kitchen tools and other foods nearby. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/7vTjLGdQY6

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Bacteria can survive in many places around your kitchen. Keep countertops and other kitchen surfaces clean to prevent cross-contamination. Keep your fridge clean, too: Wipe spills immediately and clean the inside with hot water and liquid soap. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/6FtUByocPR

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Anyone in charge of preparing part of the #Thanksgiving meal needs to wash hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds before touching foods. Foodborne bacteria can’t be seen, tasted or smelled, so make sure to clean those hands! #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/IgeUJ7OS1m

name: North Central DPH
tweet: All North Central Health District locations and offices will be closed today, Nov. 25, and tomorrow, Nov. 26 for the #Thanksgiving holiday. All services will resume Monday, Nov. 29.  https://t.co/vqT9YmjZXP

name: North Central DPH
tweet: Never thaw food at room temperature – harmful bacteria can multiply rapidly at room temperature. The safest way to thaw meat, poultry and seafood is in a refrigerator. Place the frozen food on a plate or pan to catch any juices that may leak. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/gdpQBnkyoN

name: North Central DPH
tweet: When you bring your #Thanksgiving groceries home, separate raw meat, poultry, seafood and eggs from other foods in the refrigerator. Place them in containers or sealed plastic bags on the bottom shelf of the refrigerator. #TheStoryOfYourDinner  https://t.co/dtY2qvX19N
